Write a Python application which interacts with Patchwork and ranks
patches by how ready they are to be applied. There are 3 main components
to the application:
 - state mirroring (from a remote patchwork instance)
 - interactive web UI displying currently active patches
 - DSL for defing the rules of sorting the patches.

The configuration parameters should be read from a YAML file.

Application you are writing is called Suie.

1. State mirroring

Patches are tracked in an external web application called Patchwork.
This application exposes a REST API, load the file called patchwork.yaml
to understand the API. Main object we are tracking is the series,
which consist of patches. We also need to track comments and checks
to make sorting decisions. Use the events API endpoint to track changes
and appearance of new objects.

We intend to only track a single project per instance of the application,
so expect project name or id in the config file, and query only objects
relevant to that project.

The state can be only runtime-saved, we don't need a database. When application
starts it should discover all series which are in active state and less than
a week old (the exact period of "lookback" should be read from the config).
Fetch the series and then query the checks, patches, comments related
to those series.

Provide logs for interactions with patchwork. Product a JSON file listing
the requests made to patchwork, how long they took and how many objects
were returned.

The requests to patchwork must have retries configured (use the requests
library), they may fail transiently when patchwork is overloaded.

The user agent field must be set via the config.

2. Web UI

The Web UI should be a static page which is periodically generated based
on the state gathered from patchwork. The UI needs to be interactive
(using JavaScript) but no dynamic loading of content is expected. The UI
should be regenerated any time the state of objects has changed.

The UI should group patches in series. Default display should show series
as rows, which can be unfolded to reveal patches. Apart from series ID,
author and title the main view should show the series age (how long ago
it was posted) as well as status of the related checks.

Note that since the UI is a static page we need to calculate the age in
javascript otherwise based on when patches were sent.

Read expected checks from the config file. The UI should focus on checks
which are either not passing or are missing.

The UI should have the ability to hide inactive series (default).

The UI should have the ability to hide series / patches which have a delegate
on at least on patch but none of the delegates is a delegate specified in
a drop-down in the menu.

You are allowed to use common javascript libraries.

Try to be relatively concise with out output. Roughly 30 series should
fit on a normal display.

3. Sorting DSL

The Web UI must be (statically) sorted using rules which are simple
to modify. Config should contain a path to a python file and function
name. It should load that file and run the function with parameters
needed to perform classification. The function returns relative score
used for sorting the series. Sorting should be smallest value to highest.

The system should be able to consume a JSON file (configured in config)
which allows mapping individuals to companies. Read the file called
db.json.sample to understand the format of the JSON file.

The system should be able to load developer statistics JSON file (path
form config). This file defines the reviewer score of each individual
and indirectly (using the previously mentioned file) their company.

The script should have easy access to information like:
 - reviewer score of the author and their company
 - who sent Reviewed-by or Acked-by tags for the patches (distinction between
   Reviewed-by and Acked-by is irrelevant). Reviewed-by or Acked-by tags
   should ignore those sent by people who work for the same company
   as the author
 - whether patch received any review comments, review comment is any
   email which does not include a review tag
 - not that review tags sent in response to the cover letter (patch 0),
   or containing phrases like "for the whole series" or "for the entire
   series" should be considered as review tags for each patch

The script should have the ability to report "comments" which are
lines of text explaining / diagnosing the score.

The score is evaluated for each individual patch. The score of the series
is the highest score of all its patches.


Follow up prompts

Make sure that output/patchwork_requests.json is not overriden every time the program is restarted. We should append to it. When the file gets to 10,000 entries we should dump the contents into a new file with a date appended to the name, and reset the entries to empty.

We want names of the reviewers to be listed in the UI not their email addresses.

Add at series levels two links - to the list_archive_url of the series and to the web_url of the series. The former should be called Lore, the latter Patchwork.

Reviewer summarization needs a major rework. First of all the names at the series level are truncated to just the first name for some people (but not all). This seems like a bug. Second colors of the partial reviewer at the series level is too aggressive. It should be something more mellow. For example make the full reviewer a less saturated shade of green and the partial reviewer gray. Third, at the patch level we need to highlight whether the review was present in the patch when it was posted; or it came in later in one of the comments posted to the series.

The Lore link seems to be missing. The UI has too many columns now. Put the links in the same column as the series ID, under it in separate lines. Similarly you can display the delegate and the series state in the same column, one under the other. Finally let the UI get wider for wider screens.

You got the coloring of the reviewers at patch level backwards. Make the reviews which were in the patch when posted gray and the new reviews that came in via comments the blue color that was prevously used for pre-existing ones. Once again double check your work on the reviewer names at the series level. Some series are still missing surnames (e.g. series reviewed pertially by John Doe shows John Doe in patches, but only John at the series level).

The Lore links are still missing. They only show up in the patches. Try to load them from cover letter (if the series has one) and the first patch if cover letter doesn't exist.

There's a major problem with the reviewer summarization at the series level. The reviews which came in via comments after the series was posted do not show up there at all.

Add some column names, first column with the links and IDs can be called ID. Second Author, third Title, fourth age, fifth score, sixth state, sevent reviews, eight checks. While at it please reformat the age column a little bit, remove the "ago" and make sure that we display hours even for series which are older than a day.

Refactor the displaying of the scores. Treat the score as hours, so a score of 25 should be shown as "1d 1h" a score of -7 as "-7h". Adjust the scoring example dividing the values of scores by 50 so that we don't end up with huge values.

When computing the age of a series exclude time during the weekend (Saturday and Sunday). The UI should show the age of the series which doesn't overlap with the weekend the way it's displaying it now. But if the time since series was posted overlaps with the weekend it should be shown as time exluding the weekend and then time during the weekend in brackets. For example if patch was posted on Friday and it's Monday the age may look something like 23h (+2d). Or if the series was posted during the weekend and it's Monday morning: 23h (+1d 2h). The "time in the weekend" should be displayed under the normal date to avoid making the column wider. For simplicity you can assume that a patch series will only overlap with a single weekend. Make sure that the time with and without weekend is exposed in the context to the sorting/scoring function.

We're missing review comment presence in the UI. Display review comments in the same column as the review tags, but the names of people who commented without providing a review tag for the patch should be yellow. When summaring reviewers at the series level the reviewer should be yellow if they commented without providing a review tag on at least one of the patches.

Add a warning to the logs if author of the patches is not found in ml-stats. Add info level message if reviewer / commenter is not found.

Add a chip under the author (separate line but the same column) displaying the company associate of the author.
